{"id":"0907.3873","submitter":"Michael Kleber","authors":"Thomas Colthurst, Michael Kleber","title":"A Gray path on binary partitions","comments":"This was released as a draft preprint sometime between April and July\n  2003, but the authors never revised it into a final version. Posting this to\n  the arXiv for archival purposes","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A binary partition of a positive integer $n$ is a partition of $n$ in which\neach part has size a power of two. In this note we first construct a Gray\nsequence on the set of binary partitions of $n$. This is an ordering of the set\nof binary partitions of each $n$ (or of all $n$) such that adjacent partitions\ndiffer by one of a small set of elementary transformations; here the allowed\ntransformatios are replacing $2^k+2^k$ by $2^{k+1}$ or vice versa (or addition\nof a new +1). Next we give a purely local condition for finding the successor\nof any partition in this sequence; the rule is so simple that successive\ntransitions can be performed in constant time. Finally we show how to compute\ndirectly the bijection between $k$ and the $k$th term in the sequence.\n  This answers a question posed by Donald Knuth in section 7.2.1 of The Art of\nComputer Programming.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 22 Jul 2009 16:09:48 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-07-23"}
